comments.body: When I was last advancing this, there were a number of issues affecting the Maven build process in my local environment. This required the following changes, but DataSpace can now be built for Docker or Vagrant environments: https://git.atmire.com/clients/princeton-5/-/compare/dataspace-client-DEV...jrg5-dataspace-local-dev-build

https://github.com/pulibrary/dspace-development/compare/spike-jrgriffiniii-atmire was needed in order to build DataSpace locally, but this does indeed work now. I'm going to proceed with testing this for the OAR.

Throughout the past month, there has only been one request for this:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1443986/100918387-65ad3e00-34a6-11eb-8e50-6cd0e532c8f6.png)

Does the metadata you have in the Friedberg Geniza Project (FGP) include original dimensions? That's something I've learned more recently that scholars care about, when looking at images of fragments. It seems to me that dimensions would be factual data that FGP can't claim ownership on, curious what y'all think. If there's any way to include that information now or add it later, it would be great to have; storing it in Figgy with the digitized fragments seems like the logical/preferred place to me.

marc_liberation.title: Estimate how many times we hit the alma api.

comments.body: We can track hits to our API with this: https://app.datadoghq.com/logs/analytics?agg_q=%40controller%2C%40action%2C%40format&cols=host%2Cservice%2C%40http.url_details.queryString.q%2C%40action%2C%40format&from_ts=1604271119706&index=&live=true&messageDisplay=inline&query=source%3Aruby+service%3Abibdata+-%40controller%3A%22Locations%3A%3AHoldingLocationsController%22+-%40controller%3A%22Locations%3A%3ADeliveryLocationsController%22+-%40controller%3A%22HighVoltage%3A%3APagesController%22++-%40controller%3A%22Users%3A%3AOmniauthCallbacksController%22&stream_sort=desc&to_ts=1606863119706&top_n=10&viz=query_table

I am sorry, I cannot readily find a solution for this without caching all of the bib. records, iterating through these, retrieving each of the `holding` resources for these, and then iterating through each `item`.

I will proceed with looking at the Datadog and see about determining whether or not this endpoint is accessed frequently. Following a discussion during the daily check-in meeting held today, if this is infrequently accessed, there might not be a strong case for implementing a solution for this (or, even for removing the `ItemsController` entirely), given that, as christinach indicated, this really requires that the Alma API offer an entirely new endpoint.

Throughout the past month, there has only been one request for this:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1443986/100918387-65ad3e00-34a6-11eb-8e50-6cd0e532c8f6.png)
That one request was probably me testing it a minute ago.

@mzelesky, I hope that you do not mind me tagging you, however this issue addresses the ability for users to access Items by unique identifiers for https://bibdata.princeton.edu as we are looking to migrate to the Alma API:

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/1443986/100918950-26332180-34a7-11eb-89cf-b58c04f679ab.png)

As christinach discovered, there isn't currently an Alma API endpoint that would permit us to just query for Item records using *only* the Item ID (we would need to pass the bib. ID and holding ID for the Item as well). However, reviewing the usage metrics for bibdata.princeton.edu, it doesn't really appear as if users are using this on any regular basis.

Might you or any of your colleagues use this on any regular basis? Is there any reason to consider this essential to port to the Alma-based implementation of bibdata?

I personally don't use bibdata's APIs for any of my work, and I don't think anyone else in Enterprise Services uses it. It's possible some catalogers use it (specifically Don Thornbury or Tom Ventimiglia), but in Alma, it's entirely possible they'll be able to do whatever work uses this endpoint in Alma itself.
Understood, thank you for confirming this @mzelesky.
